</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="77A250A2FF6986ADD9A8C66BFA8D7DDF" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3F070329FF6986ADD9A8C66BFEE5781C" blockId="191.[136,778,173,2070]" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD9A8C66BFED67968" bold="true" box="[189,305,1091,1117]" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Remarks.</emphasis>
For a full description see 
<bibRefCitation id="5B297ED8FF6986ADDB78C66BFE9779B5" author="Shcherbachev, Y. N. &amp; Iwamoto, T." pageId="191" pageNumber="192" pagination="285 - 314" refId="ref299772" refString="Shcherbachev, Y. N. &amp; Iwamoto, T. (1995) Indian Ocean grenadiers of the subgenus Coryphaenoides, genus Coryphaenoides (Macrouridae, Gadiformes, Pisces). California Academy of Sciences, 48, 285 - 314." type="journal article" year="1995">Shcherbachev &amp; Iwamoto (1995)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD896C64DFD43794A" box="[387,676,1125,1151]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD896C64DFD43794A" box="[387,676,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Coryphaenoides microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be a sister species to 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD8BCC6A0FD0E7994" authority="Steindachner" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[425,745,1159,1186]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD8BCC6A0FDAB7994" box="[425,588,1160,1186]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
Steindachner
</taxonomicName>
&amp; D̂derlein, 1887 known from 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF6986ADD8C8C682FDFA79F1" box="[477,541,1194,1220]" name="Japan" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Japan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF6986ADDB42C682FD7879F1" box="[599,671,1194,1220]" name="South Korea" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Korea</collectingCountry>
. The two species are parapatric, with their distributions only slightly overlapping in the Sea of 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF6986ADD8B7C6C6FE05783D" box="[418,482,1262,1288]" name="Japan" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Japan</collectingCountry>
off 
<collectingCountry id="47AF43B9FF6986ADDB18C6C6FDB6783D" box="[525,593,1262,1288]" name="South Korea" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Korea</collectingCountry>
(Appendix 3-6F and 3-7A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F070329FF6986ADD9A8C719FA8D7DDF" blockId="191.[136,778,173,2070]" lastBlockId="191.[810,1451,173,234]" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD9A8C719FDA2787E" bold="true" box="[189,581,1329,1355]" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Relationships and comparisons.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADDB47C719FF067858" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADDB47C719FF067858" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Coryphaenoides microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD8BCC77CFDA87858" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[425,591,1364,1390]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD8BCC77CFDA87858" box="[425,591,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (see the Relationships of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD858C75EFE1778BA" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[333,496,1398,1424]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD858C75EFE1778BA" box="[333,496,1398,1424]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD99DC7B0FECF7884" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[136,296,1432,1458]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD99DC7B0FECF7884" box="[136,296,1432,1458]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD8BEC7B0FDC27884" box="[427,549,1432,1458]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD8BEC7B0FDC27884" box="[427,549,1432,1458]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
readily differs from 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD99DC792FECE78E6" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[136,297,1466,1492]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD99DC792FECE78E6" box="[136,297,1466,1492]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that the spinules on the body scales are arranged in tightly packed, narrowly convergent rows (vs. tightly packed parallel rows), with the tip of the last spinule in each row extending distinctly beyond the posterior scale margin (vs. scarcely reaching this level) (
<figureCitation id="A7831FACFF6986ADD985C44BFF097B4B" box="[144,238,1635,1662]" captionStart="FIGURE 122" captionStartId="190.[136,235,1739,1763]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,158,1708]" captionTargetId="figure-79@190.[151,1436,158,1708]" captionTargetPageId="190" captionText="FIGURE 122. Scanning electron micrographs showing body scales (from the dorsum below the interdorsal space) of three species of the Coryphaenoides marginatus group. (A–B) C. marginatus, BSKU 103048, 71.4 mm HL; (C–D) C. microps, ASIZP 66413, 43.7 mm HL; (E–F) C. nasutus, BSKU 103042, 78.5 mm HL. (A, C, E) Views from above; (B, D, F) oblique views. [Photos: NSMT]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6423052" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6423052/files/figure.png" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
C–D vs. A–B). 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD88BC44BFD517B48" box="[414,694,1635,1661]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD88BC44BFD517B48" box="[414,694,1635,1661]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Coryphaenoides microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
further differs from that species in having a smaller orbit (19–22% HL vs. 22–31%) and a longer postorbital (50–55% HL vs. 42–51%). In the four 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD899C4E2FDED7BD6" box="[396,522,1738,1764]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD899C4E2FDED7BD6" box="[396,522,1738,1764]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens examined, the underside of the head was almost fully scaled along the infraorbital, preopercular, and mandibular canals, and naked areas were apparent only on anterior portions of the mandibular rami and a narrow band above the upper lip. In contrast, the 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD865C55CFDF47AB8" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[368,531,1908,1934]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD865C55CFDF47AB8" box="[368,531,1908,1934]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens examined had broad naked areas above the upper lip and along margins of the interopercle, preopercle, and mandibular rami. 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD9DFC5F2FE067AC6" box="[202,481,2010,2036]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="microps">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD9DFC5F2FE067AC6" box="[202,481,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">Coryphaenoides microps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unlikely to be confused with females of 
<taxonomicName id="F8B878AAFF6986ADD82CC5D4FE3F7520" authorityName="Steindachner &amp; Doderlein" authorityYear="1887" box="[313,472,2044,2070]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coryphaenoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gadiformes" pageId="191" pageNumber="192" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="marginatus">
<emphasis id="0DCCDF3BFF6986ADD82CC5D4FE3F7520" box="[313,472,2044,2070]" italics="true" pageId="191" pageNumber="192">C. marginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a uniformly dark body (vs. paler ventrally) and blackish fins (vs. first dorsal and pelvic fins pale except for dark distal margins).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
